<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="1TI" stage="Final" version="D">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:54:52Z" when="2009-10-05 05:54:52Z" stage="Draft">Consultant checked April 2006 with Dave Glasgow; checked *priest, a'a-ari, Jahudi, June 2007</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">1 Timotius</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">1 Timotius<bt>1 Timotius</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Sasuri Paulus ka èci<bt>Paulus' first letter</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">hia angalai na Timotius<bt>to his friend Timotius</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii maho'o<bt>Greetings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-2" />Timotius dhu be'a.<bt>Dear Timotius</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lii maho'o nèti ja'a, Paulus. Ama Lamatua ded'e le ja'a j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus Kristus. Aa Lamatua Yesus, era sanao-maena dhu hia èdhi mamuri taa-taa dènge Nèngu, lula Ama Lamatua pakaj'èu èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo.<bt>Greetings from me, Paulus. God has elevated/appointed me to be Yesus Kristus' servant/*apostle (doublet). And the Lord Yesus, is still the hope (doublet) who gives us-inc eternal life/salvation with Him [CHECK grammar; different than KM], because Father God is the one who has separated/rescued/saved2 us from sins (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abalaa = abis sapu rata ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">abalaa = abis sapu rata ; cèku = ja'a</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Timotius! Èu ne, nuka sèmi ana matana ja'a, lula ja'a ka dhu pad'elo j'ara ka èu parcaya Kristus. Ja'a sabaj'a sèna ka Ama Lamatua èdhi, dènge Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, pad'elo d'ara hua iia Rèngu, aa hia èu mamuri dènge mera-milu.<bt>Timotius! You are like my own birth son, because I am the one who shoed the way for you-sg to believe in Kristus. I pray that our-inc Father God, and Yesus Kristus who is our Head, show Their goodness/grace/kindness, and give you a life of peace/calmness</bt><note reference="1:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 16:1</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku pamud'e dènge dhèu dhu aj'a lii lolo lèke boe<bt>Be careful with people who give untrue/incorrect teaching(s)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Uru èèna, dua ti ètu kota Epesus. Lod'o ja'a neo laku asa propensi Makedonia, ja'a manèngi èu ho pea ètu Epesus. Te lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu dhu pab'ingu dhèu sarani sèra dènge aj'a j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke boe. De ja'a manèngi sèna ka èu lamu kai si, ho ra loe eele ka.<bt>Back then, the two of us-inc were together in the city of Epesus. When I wanted to go to the province of Makedonia, I pressured you to stay in Epesus. Cuz (elaboration) at that time, there were people who were confusing the Christians by teaching things that were not correct. So (consequently) I asked you to go forbid/block them, so they would stop.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamud'e = remeh, enteng ; Baku"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pamud'e = remeh, enteng ; Baku pamud'e = mage-mage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kathws: just as, just like parakalesa:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kathws: just as, just like parakalesa: to urge, ask, request, advise, encourage<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>prosmeinai: remain, stay poreuomenos: going, proceeding, travelling<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>hina: so that, in order that paraggellw: give orders, insist, command, direct<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>heterodidaskalein: different teaching, false doctrine LITERALLY: Just as I requested you to stay in Ephesus when I was going into Macedonia, that you should command certain ones not to teach other doctrines<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Aa dhèu sèra core eele lod'o iia d'ara kahèi lasi palolo nanuku, pab'ala lii dènge kapod'e-kabèli nèti bèi-baki toke lai ana lai èpu. J'ara sèmi sèra, dhoka hia dhèu patao-palaha, aa hia boe ra mamuri dènge parcaya mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>And those people are also wasting time needlessly and go around arguing/squabbling over nonsensical fabes/fairy tales/myths, and arguing twistedly about ancestors and descendants. Those (sorts of) things only make people fight, and don't make them live and believe in God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dènge boe kabua = tidak ada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">dènge boe kabua = tidak ada harga ; nanuku = dongeng</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mede: and not, neither prosexein: pay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">mede: and not, neither prosexein: pay attention to, devote attention to, give heed to, take notice of, spend time on<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>muthois: myths, legends, fables, senseless stories genealogiais: genealogies, list of ancestor names<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>aperantois: endless, long haitines: which<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>ekzeteseis: useless speculation, arguments, questions, controversies parexousin: cause, produce, promote<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>mallon: rather, instead of oikonomian: training, work, plan, building up, edifying. "Strong" is not what he's talking about. CHECK PARALLELS.<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>pistei: faith LITERALLY: neither to pay attention to myths and long genealogies, which cause arguments instead of the way of God which is by faith;<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ja'a holo èu, sèna ka èu aj'a dhèu parcaya sèra ho mamuri pasue èci dènge èci kahèi. Sasue ra hud'i mai nèti d'ara dhu mèu, nèti ngangee dhu mola, aa nèti parcaya dhu koe-kapengo boe.<bt>I am advising you, so that you also teach believers to live in reciprocal love/pity with each other. Their love must come from clean insides (=pure motives), from correct/straight thinking, and from faith/belief that is serious/not trivial/not playing around.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Use terms in lists uniformly in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">Use terms in lists uniformly in 5T's. telos: end, purpose, goal, aim, outcome<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>paraggelias: command, order, charge agape: love<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>katharas: clean, pure, unselfish kardias: heart<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>suneidesews: conscience, judging ourselves agathes: good<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>pistews: faith anupokritou: genuine, sincere, true; this is presented negatively as "without putting on an act, unfeigned, not a show, no shibai". LEX: no throw (da) ack.<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>LITERALLY: the purpose of the command is love from a clean heart, and a good conscience, and sincere faith,</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te ngaa abhu mese cahag'e dhu kako sala le j'ara, ra tèke eele lii holo-nori. Hèia lasi core eele lod'o iia d'ara dènge padhue-padhai j'ara-j'ara dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua.<bt>But there are some teachers who have deviated far and abandoned that advice. So they go and waste time arguing about things that have no goal or basis (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dènge boe kolo-kapua = sonde ada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">dènge boe kolo-kapua = sonde ada ujung pohon</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tines: same as &quot;get guys&quot; in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">tines: same as "get guys" in v. 3. astokheesantes: miss the mark, lose the way<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>eksetrapesan: turn away, turn aside, wander away, give up, swerve mataiologian: fruitless talk, useless talk, empty talk, foolish discussions<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>LITERALLY: from which some have lost their way, turning aside to useless talk,</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Rèngu padedha iisi ra, peka na, rèngu mese dhu aj'a madhutu atora Musa. Ra tao iisi ra sèmi mese aae, te ngaa re'a boe ngaa dhu rèngu aj'a-nori èèna.<bt>They elevate themselves saying they are teachers who teach according to the Law of Musa. They behave.in.the.style of important teachers/professors, but they don't know/understand what they teach (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thelontes: desire, want nomodidaskaloi: teachers of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">thelontes: desire, want nomodidaskaloi: teachers of the law<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>noountes: understand legousin: say<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>diabebaiountai: confidently affirm, assert, speak confidently, insist LITERALLY: desiring to be teachers of the law, they neither understand what they are saying nor what they insist on.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti te'a, huku Musa èèna be'a, sad'i èdhi pake ne madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua.<bt>We-inc all know that the Law of Musa is good, as long as we-inc use it in accord with Father God's true purpose/intention.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao pamèci = buat sesuai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">tao pamèci = buat sesuai</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oidamen: know kalos: good|i(8) (8) |rnomos:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">oidamen: know kalos: good<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>nomos: law nomimws: according to the rules, lawfully, properly, in the right way<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>khreetai: use LITERALLY: But we know that the law is good if anyone uses it in the right way,<span class="Italic">(8)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Atora sèra suri boe hia mi dhèu dhu mamuri mola le. Te ngaa pala mi dhèu palab'a, dhu d'èi boe nanene paredha, dhu mamuri pakaj'èu nèti Lamatua, dhu d'èi ad'u-ue bhelu-katub'a, dhu pusi-pahae boe Lamatua, dhu pamud'e j'ara-j'ara dhu hua iia, dhu tuka pamadhe dhèu, dènge dhu pamadhe ina dènge ama ra.<bt>Those Laws/Regulations were not written for people whose lives are right(eous)/correct/true. But, it was handed down for people who are rebels/troublemakers, (those) who don't like to listen/obey commands, (those) who live far from God/Lord, (those) who like to do evil, (those) who don't care.about/give.attention to God1, (those) who belittle/scorn/disparage things that are good2, (those) who (habitually) kill/murder people, and (those) who murder their own father and mother.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eidws: know dikaiw: righteous, upright, just|i(9)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">eidws: know dikaiw: righteous, upright, just<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>keitai: exist anomois: lawless, lawbreaker<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>anupotaktois: undisciplined, disobedient, criminals, rebellious, unruly, insubordinate asebesi: godless, ungodly, irreverent. TERM: ack jalike God notting<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>hamartwlois: sinners, defies God by outward act anosiois: unholy, not religious, irreligious, lack of inner purity<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>bebelois: profane, scoffers, mockers, treat religion with contempt matrolwais: killer of mother<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>patrolwais: killer of father androphonois: murderer<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>LITERALLY: knowing this, that the law does not exist for the righteous person, but for the lawbreakers and rebellious, irreverent and sinners, impure and scoffers, killers of mothers and killers of fathers, murderers,</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Atora sèra suri kahèi hia dhèu kajeo dènge bhèni do dènge mone, aa mone dhu tao j'ara makae dènge mone, dhu rai rèti dhèu ho sui dènge doi-dhari, dhèu dhu kapod'e-kabèli, dhu j'aj'i sakasii omo koso, aa hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu d'èi palab'a lii aj'a dhu lèke.<bt>Those Laws are also written for people who are naughty with females or with males, males who do shameful things with males, (those) who snatch people to ransom them for money (covers both kidnappers and slave traders), people who often deceive/con artists, (those) who are false/lying witnesses, and for all people who like to oppose true/correct/right teaching.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kajeo = nakal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">kajeo = nakal</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pornois: fornicator, sexually immoral arsevokoitais: male"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pornois: fornicator, sexually immoral arsevokoitais: male homosexual<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>andrapodistais: slave dealer, slave traders, kidnapper pseustais: liar<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>epiorkois: perjured, false testimony, swear a lie is the truth heteros: another of a different kind<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>hugiainouse: be healthy, sound, true didaskalia: teaching<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>antikeitai: be opposed, contrary LITERALLY: for sexually immoral persons, male homosexuals, kidnappers, liars, those who give false testimony, and any other thing contrary to sound teaching,<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />A'aj'a dhu lèke sèra, mai nèti Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua dhu Na pangèd'u mi ja'a. Aa Lamatua èèna, Ama Lamatua dhu kapai risi eele. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu ded'e Ne padedha-dedha.<bt>Right teachings come from God's Good News, which He has given/turned.over to me. And that Lord, is Father God who is excessively great. That is why people praise (Idiom: elevate very high) Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="euaggelion: good news, gospel dokses: glorious|i(11)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">euaggelion: good news, gospel dokses: glorious<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>makariou: fortunate, in a good state, blessed; NEB "eternal felicity". TERM. Not eulogeetos "people say good things about him or wish him well". episteuthen: entrust<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>LITERALLY: according to the good news of the glorious and blessed God, which was entrusted to me.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, lula d'ara Na hua iia<bt>Give thanks to Father God, because of His goodness/kindness/grace</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ja'a manèngi makasi ae-ae mi Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, lula Na lèka ja'a, ka Na hia ja'a bisa pakako sasab'a Na.<bt>I give lots of thanks to our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, because He trusted me, and He made me able to carry.out His work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="xapin: thank endunamwsanti: strengthen, give strength,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">xapin: thank endunamwsanti: strengthen, give strength, enable<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>piston: trustworthy, faithful, worthy egesato: consider, know,<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>themenos: appoint, put into dikonian: service, ministry<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>LITERALLY: I thank Christ Jesus our Lord, who gives me strength, because he considered me faithful, appointing me for the ministry,</Message></Annotation><v n="13-14" />Masi ka uru èèna, ja'a d'èi padhai pa'ele iie kolongara Yesus, aa paj'èra dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu j'ara mamuri Na. Ja'a d'èi ènyi raruri si. Bhabhelu ja'a sèmi èèna, lula uru èèna, ja'a ke'a boe ngaa dhu ja'a tao, aa parcaya mèka Yesus Kristus. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua core eele boe ja'a. Ka Na pad'elo sasue Na mi ja'a.<bt>Whereas formerly, I often rubbished (Idiom: spoke making rotten to cause to fall) Yesus' name/reputation, and caused suffering for the people who followed/obeyed His way of life. I often oppressed destroying them [SVC action-resulting state]. My evil was like that because at that former time, I didn't understand what I was doing, and [I] didn't yet believe in Yesus Kristus. But He didn't discard me. And He showed His love/pity to me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ènyi = tekan, tendes ; raruri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">ènyi = tekan, tendes ; raruri = ulik ; tibha = buang (not known)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="proteron: earlier, in the past, formerly"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">proteron: earlier, in the past, formerly blasphemon: blasphemous, slanderous, speak evil<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>diwkten: persecutor, religious persecutor hubristen: insolent, insult, injurious, violent<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>eleethen: have mercy agnown: be ignorant<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>epoiesa: do, act apistia: unbelief<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: formerly being a blasphemer and persecutor and violent; but I was shown mercy, because I did it ignorantly in unbelief,</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:3, 9:4-5</note>Mia hari Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus, loe boe pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi ja'a! Nèngu hia mèngi-nale dhu ae hia ja'a, sèna ka ja'a bisa parcaya Ne, aa ja'a bisa sue dhèu leo kahèi nuka sèmi Nèngu sue ja'a.<bt>Furthermore, the Yesus Kristus, our Lord, never ceased showing me His goodness/kindness/grace! He gave abundant blessings to me, so that I could believe in Him, and I could love other people just like He loves me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huperepleonasen: be abundant, overflow xaris: favor,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">huperepleonasen: be abundant, overflow xaris: favor, grace, goodwill<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: but the favor of our Lord overflowed with the faith and love which is in Christ Jesus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èdhi biasa tadèngi le, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus Kristus mai le asa rai-haha, ho pala-bagi mamuri mi dhèu dhu ad'u-ue sasala.&gt;&gt; Mema tare'a sèmi èèna! Nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra dhu ad'u-ue sasala, ja'a ka dhu bhelu risi eele.<bt>We-inc have often heard that, &lt;&lt;Yesus Kristus has come into this world to distribute life/salvation people who have done wrong/sinned.&gt;&gt; That is certainly true! Among everyone who has done wrong, I am the most evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pistos: trustworthy, faithful, true, sure logos:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pistos: trustworthy, faithful, true, sure logos: word, message<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>apodoxes: acceptance aksios: worthy, deserve<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>hamartwlous: sinner swsai: to save<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>prwtos: first, chief, foremost LITERALLY: The message is true and deserves full acceptance, that Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners; of whom I am first,<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Masi ka ja'a bhelu sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua huku boe ja'a. Te nare ja'a j'aj'i mi tadha sena ka pad'elo sasue Yesus Kristus mi dhèu dhu bhelu risi eele, nuka sèmi ja'a ne'e ne. Dènge j'ara ne'e ka, dhèu leo dhu tao sala sèra bisa parcaya Ne kahèi, ka ra abhu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ne.<bt>Even though I was so evil like that, nevertheless God did not punish me. Cuz (elaboration) He wanted to use me as an example/sign to show Yesus Kristus' love/pity to people who are most evil like I am. In that way, other people who do wrong can also believe in Him, so they can get life continually with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="endeiksetai: show, demonstrate, display hapasan: full,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">endeiksetai: show, demonstrate, display hapasan: full, unlimited, endless, perfect, utmost<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>prootooi: prime example, foremost makrothumian: patience, longsuffering, forbearance<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>hupotupwsin: model, pattern, example mellontwn: be about to<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>LITERALLY: but because of this I received mercy, in order that in me first, Christ Jesus might show full patience, to be an example for those who were going to believe on him for eternal life.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua!<bt>Praise God's name/reputation!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula dhoka Nèngu di, Ama Lamatua;<bt>Because only He is Father God;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu leo aad'o!<bt>there is no other!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu ne, Dhèu Aae dhu paredha taa-taa.<bt>He is the King who rules/governs eternally.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mamuri Na dènge boe too-lane.<bt>His life is without boundaries.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dènge boe too-lane = tidak ada"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">dènge boe too-lane = tidak ada batas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mamadhe aad'o ètu Nèngu.<bt>There is no death in Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu bisa boe rèdhi Ne dènge musi madha.<bt>People can't see Him with their own eyeballs.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Pakab'ua dènge koa-kio aa'i-aa'i hia mi Nèngu di!<bt>All honour and praise is given just to Him!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tare'a-re'a sèmi èèna.<bt>It's truly like that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="basilei: king aiwnwn: eternal, of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">basilei: king aiwnwn: eternal, of the ages<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>aphthartw: imperishable, immortal, incorruptible aoratw: invisible<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>monw: only time: honor, respect<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>doksa: glory, praise LITERALLY: To the eternal King, immortal, invisible, the only God, be honor and glory forever and ever. Amen.<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ana Timotius dhu be'a! Ja'a neo peka dènge èu ngaa dhu hud'i èu tao ku ètu d'ara sasab'a-la'a èu. Aa'i-aa'i se, madhutu ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua peka tèke le lula-nèti èu ne. Ladhe èu madhutu lii se'e dènge mola-mola, èu sèmi ca dhèu sordad'u dhu bisa pamusu dènge be'a, ho lab'a bhabhelu-katub'a.<bt>Dear child (no age implication) Timotius! I want to tell/let you know what it is that you must do in your job/work. All these things are in accord with what God's *spokesmen/prophets have foretold about yourself. If you truly follow/obey those words, you are like a soldier who can battle/fight well, opposing those who are evil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pareggalian: from verse 3 &amp; 5"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pareggalian: from verse 3 &amp; 5 paratithemai: place beside, entrust, commit, give<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>teknon: child, son proagousas: lead, go before, lead the way, precede<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>propheteias: prophecy strateue: do military service, serve in the army, fight<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>strateian: campaign, warfare kalen: good<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>LITERALLY: This command I place beside you, son Timothy, according to the prophecies which went before you, so that you may fight a good fight,</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Kèpe pa'èra-èra lalèka èu mi Yesus Kristus. Aa j'aga paie, sèna ka d'ara èu mola taruu. Te abhu kahèi dhèu leo dhu ro'o heka nanene d'ara iiki ra, dhu pa'ele iie parcaya rèngu, nuka sèmi kapa rage nare hadhu aae.<bt>Hold tightly/firmly to your faith/belief in Kristus. And take care that your insides are clean/pure always. Cuz (elaboration) there are also other people who aren't willing to listen to their consciences (lit: small insides), who destroy their faith/belief, just like a ship that has run aground on a (coral) reef.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara iiki = hati nurani"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">dara iiki = hati nurani</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="suneigesin: conscience apwsamenoi: reject, not listen"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">suneigesin: conscience apwsamenoi: reject, not listen to<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>enauagesan: suffer shipwreck, make a mess, ruin LITERALLY: having faith and a good conscience, which some have rejected, and have shipwrecked their faith;<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Himeneus dènge Aleksander si, ra sèmi èèna ka! Nèti èèna ka, ja'a soro le rèngu asa dhèu aae nidhu. Ja'a tao sèmi èèna, sèna ka aj'a si loe eele pakarehe kolongara Lamatua,<bt>Himeneus and Aleksander are just like that! That is why I have handed them over to the *devil. I did that to teach them to stop damaging/disparaging God's name/reputation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paredwka: give over, hand over, deliver."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paredwka: give over, hand over, deliver. Also "hand um ova to da Devil" [1 Cor 5:5], but this fits better here. Satanaai: da Devil<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>paideuthwsin: be instructed, be taught, learn blasphemein: blaspheme, slander, speak evil<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>LITERALLY: who are Hymenaios and Alexander, whom I have given over to Satan, so that they may learn not to blaspheme.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Atora pakaboko dhèu sarani<bt>Regulations for [when] Christians gather</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Dhu uru tèka miu tao: ja'a manèngi miu sabaj'a hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Ladhe miu mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua, manèngi sèna ka Na ladhe-leru dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu d'ara j'aj'èra. Aa manèngi makasi, lula Na tao le babe'a mi rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>The first/prior thing you must do: I ask you-pl to pray1 for all people. When you pray2 to Father God, ask Him to watch over/take care of all people who are in suffering. And give thanks, because He has done good to all of them. [EXEG: "who are in difficulty" explicating "intercessions"; if stop at "all" reduntant with 1st sentence.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kasasi = ibadat rumah-tangga, hari jadi,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">kasasi = ibadat rumah-tangga, hari jadi, pengucapan syukur (di luar rumah gereja)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parakalew: direct, urge, exhort, appeal to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">parakalew: direct, urge, exhort, appeal to prwtos: first<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>poiew: do, make deesis: prayer, supplications, prayer for needs<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>proseuxe: prayer with reverence because of who God is -- current draft emphasizes details too much enteuksis: prayer, intercessions, intercede, request on behalf of others, petition<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>euxaristia: thanksgiving, prayer of thanksgiving huper: concerning, on behalf of, for<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>LITERALLY: I direct, therefore, first of all, that requests, prayers, intercessions, and prayers of thanksgiving be made for all people.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Sabaj'a sèmi èèna kahèi hia dhèu aae-dhèu aae, dènge dhèu dhu rèd'u paredha. Dènge j'ara ne'e èdhi bisa mamuri mera-milu, dènge dame, madhutu dad'èi Lamatua, mamuri pamèci dènge dhèu dhu pahaha iisi mi Lamatua.<bt>Also pray like that for the kings and people who hold government. In that way we-inc can live in calmness (doublet), in relational peace, according to the will of God, living in a way appropriate for people who humble themselve to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèci = yg berkenan, cocok,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pamèci = yg berkenan, cocok,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="basileus: king huperoxe: prominence, high position|i(2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">basileus: king huperoxe: prominence, high position<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>eremos: tranquil, quiet, still hesuxeos: quiet, restful, peaceful<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>bios: life, earthly life, physical life diagw: spend one's life, lead one's life, live<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>eusebeia: godliness, religious devotion, piety, duty to God, religion in daily life semnotes: dignity, seriousness, respectfulness, reverence, holiness, gravity, honesty<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: for kings and all who are in high positions, so that we may live a quiet and restful life in all godliness and dignity.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Manèngi-mangaj'i sèmi èèna ka dhu be'a. J'ara ne'e ne ka pakarej'e d'ara Lamatua, dhu hia èdhi mamuri.<bt>Praying (doublet) like that is good. These ways will please the insides of God, who gives us life/salvation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalos: good, morally good, noble, praiseworthy,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kalos: good, morally good, noble, praiseworthy, apodektos: pleasing, acceptable<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>enwpion: before, in the sight of, in the opinion of swter: savior, saving character of<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>LITERALLY: This is good and pleasing to our savior God,</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dad'èi Lamatua ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra abhu mamuri, aa re'a mia ka dhu lèke. Nuka sèmi:<bt>God's will is for all people to obtain/get life/salvation, and know what is true. Like:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="thelw: desire, want something definite, wish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">thelw: desire, want something definite, wish swzw: be saved, be preserved, be delivered<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>epignwsis: knowledge, recognition, realization aletheia: truth, content of Christianity as truth<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>erxomai: come, brought to realization LITERALLY: who desires all people to be saved and to come into the knowledge of truth.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Ama Lamatua èèna, dhoka èci di.<bt>Father God, is only one.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa kalete dhoka èci di dhu padame èdhi dhèu rai-haha dènge Ama Lamatua, nuka, Yesus Kristus.<bt>And there is only one bridge that brings relational peace between Father God and we-inc humans, that is, Yesus Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Yesus tare'a-re'a dhèu rai-haha.<bt>And that Yesus, really is human.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mesites: mediator, arbitrator, one who mediates"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">mesites: mediator, arbitrator, one who mediates between two parties to remove a disagreement or reach a common goal, advocate, spokesman between two parties LITERALLY: For there is one God, and one mediator between God and people, the man Christ Jesus,<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Na soro iisi Na, ho sui èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti nèti sasala-sasigo èdhi.<bt>He gave over/handed over/surrendered Himself to ransom/redeem us all from our sins (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lèke dènge lod'o na, ka Ama Lamatua bhoke le pasaraa lii lolo be'a èèna hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>At the right time, Father God revealed clearly the good story to all people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="didwmi: give antilutros: ransom, redeem, payment"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">didwmi: give antilutros: ransom, redeem, payment to free someone. (used only here)<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>marturios: testimony, witness, attested kaipos: time, definite time<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>idios: ones own LITERALLY: who gave himself as a ransom for all, the testimony in his own time;<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Hèia Ama Lamatua hag'e nare ja'a j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Na, sèna ka laku peka-padhai dènge dhèu Yahudi boe ètu mia-mia, aa nori si sèna ka ra parcaya Lamatua Yesus, dènge mamuri madhutu j'ara dhu lèke. Ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne, tare'a-re'a sèmi èèna. Ja'a leko-monya boe.<bt>Then Father God selected me out to be His *apostle, so that I could go tell people who are not Yahudi everywhere, and teach them so they believe in the Lord Yesus, and live according to ways that are true. What I am saying, is really truly like that. I am not lying/deceiving.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tithemi: make, appoint keruks: herald, preacher,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">tithemi: make, appoint keruks: herald, preacher, announcer, messenger<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>apostolos: apostle, sent with a mission, sent for a purpose aletheia: truth<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>legw: say pseudomai: lie<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>didaskalos: teacher ethnos: nation, people, heathen, pagans, Gentiles<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>pistis: faith, what is believed LITERALLY: for which I was made a preacher and apostle--I speak the truth, I do not lie--a teacher of faith and truth to the nations<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Timotius 1:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Dad'èi ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: ladhe ètu mia-mia miu pakaboko ho manèngi-mangaj'i, hud'i dènge ku d'ara dhu mola-mèci. Baku panasa. Baku patao-palaha. Ladhe sabaj'a, bisa ded'e kacui-aai asa Ama Lamatua, ho j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, d'ara miu mola-mèci tare'a-re'a.<bt>My desire is like this: Whenever/wherever you-pl gather to pray (doublet), you must do it with honest/straight insides. Don't be reciprocally angry. Don't argue with each other (doublet). When you pray, [you] can lift hands to Father God, as a sign that your insides are truly clean/holy (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boulomai: desire, want, will (more determined"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">boulomai: desire, want, will (more determined than thelw) ; Nyland says the opposite /boulomai/ is less than /thelw/ and can indicate "a mere inclination" (which fits the context of this verse in contrast to vs.4) proseuxomai: pray, public prayer, prayer with reverence<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>andras: man, male (in contrast with "women" in vs. 9) topos: place<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>epairw: lift up, raise, hold up hosios: pious, devout, holy, pleasing to God<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>kheira: hand -- "holy hands" is metonymy; it's holy people, engaging in public prayer using one of the gestures that people used then. The idea is that if they are good people, then praying in public means something; if they aren't good people, then they are just showing off their religion. Focus is on clean lives. (See also Nyland) xwris: apart from, without<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>orge: anger, indignation, wrath dialogismos: dispute, argument, doubt<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: I desire therefore the men should pray in every place, raising holy hands without anger and argument;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9-10" />Dad'èi ja'a kahèi ladhe dhèu-dhèu bhèni re'a lalau iisi ra pake mèdha-papake dhu pantas. Dhu tao bhèni j'aj'i bhèni iia, lula boe nèti pasaraga rèu kètu, do pake mèdha-papake dhu kab'ua aae dhu nèti makae, do pake risi eele mèdha hualaa, doi pudhi dènge mutiara.<bt>My desire is that females know how to manage/arrange themselves using appropriate (loan) clothing. [TN] What makes women female-pretty, is not because they decorate their hair, or wear expensive clothes which bring shame/embarrassment, or excessively wear gold, silver, or pearls (loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahua iia = yg layak, tidak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pahua iia = yg layak, tidak terlalu menyolok, mahal-mahal, nilai kesopanan ; pasaraga = kasi gaga</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dadèi ja'a ka ladhe rèngu lalau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">Dadèi ja'a ka ladhe rèngu lalau iisi ra pahua iia, aa pake mèdha papake dhu be'a.</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:9-10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Petrus 3:3</note>Te dhu tao bhèni sèra j'aj'i bhèni iia, nuka d'ara dhu hua iia, aa rèngu tao dhoka j'ara dhu be'a. Èèna ka pamèci dènge dhèu bhèni dhu pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) what makes woemn female-beautiful, is beautiful insides/character, and just doing good things. That is what is appropriate for women who worship/humble themselves to Father God.</bt><v n="11" />Ladhe dhèu sarani pakaboko ho nanene lii holo-nori, na, bhèni sa kahèi madhutu atora, sèna ka pasa dhilu ra be'a-be'a ho nanene lii holo-nori dènge d'ara kateme. Baku pagagai sèna ka tao maruru.<bt>[vs 11-15 note discussion in Kroeger &amp; Kroeger, 1992]. [the obediently/submissively Gk term is seen as "behaviour appropriate to public assembly so all can receive teaching.&gt;&gt; following higher level theme.] If/when Christians gather to listen to teaching, women should also follow regulations, so that they listen carefully to the teaching wholeheartedly. Don't be reciprocally nudging and causing disturbances.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pagagai = korek"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pagagai = korek</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Madhutu ngangee ja'a, lèke boe ladhe dhèu bhèni ded'e ngi'u ra ho paredha aa aj'a dhèu mone. Be'a risi bhèni sèra taha d'ara.<bt>According to my thinking, it is not right for women to elevate themselves to command and teach men. It is better for women to restrain themselves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taha dara = sabar, mau iisi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">taha dara = sabar, mau iisi = diam seketika</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Te Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i uuru Adam, heka Hawa kèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Father God created Adam first, and only then Hawa.</bt><note reference="2:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 2:7, 2:21-22</note><v n="14" />Aa Adam dhu uru boe lèke ag'o nèti dhèu aae nidhu, te ngaa dhèu bhèni. Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, dhèu rai-haha mulai lab'a paredha Ama Lamatua.<bt>And Adam was not the first to be deceived by the *devil, but the woman. Beginning from that day/time, humans began to oppose the command/order of Father God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ag'o = tipu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">ag'o = tipu</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 3:1-6</note><v n="15" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa dhèu bhèni abhu mamuri lula rèngu rara iisi ana. Sad'i rèngu parcaya tare'a-re'a mi Kristus, mamuri pasue, mamuri dènge d'ara mola-mèci, aa mamuri madhutu j'ara dhu lèke.<bt>Even though it is like that, nevertheless women will get life/salvation because they give birth to children. As long as they truly believe in Kristus, live reciprocally loving, live with clean-pure (doublet) insides, and live according to the correct/right way.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Atora ho ded'e ca dhèu kètu juma'at<bt>Regulations for becoming a head-leader of a congregation (loan)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Mema tare'a sèmi lii dhèu, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu neo j'aj'i kètu juma'at, nèngu hag'e nare le sasab'a èci dhu hua iia titu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>It is true what people say, that, &lt;&lt;A person who wants to become head-leader of a congregation, s/he has chosen a very good work.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pistos: trustworthy, sure, certain logos: word,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pistos: trustworthy, sure, certain logos: word, saying<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>episkopos: overseer, bishop oregw: aspire to, strive fo, desire<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>epithumew: desire LITERALLY: This saying is trustworthy: if anyone aspires to be a bishop, he desires a good task.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Kètu juma'at èèna, hud'i dhèu dhu kolongara be'a. Nèngu hud'i satia dènge dhèu èmu na ca dhèu di. Nèngu hud'i taha nare d'ara na, dhèu dhu patao-palaha boe, dhu dhèu pakab'ua ne, dhu d'èi bhoke babèdho èmu ho dhèu lasi pangad'o dènge ne, aa bisa aj'a-nori dhèu leo.<bt>Head-leaders of a congregation(s) must be people who have a good name/reputation. S/He must live faithfully with just one spouse. S/He must know how to restrain/control himself, be a person who does not easily argue, whom people respect him, who enjoys opening the door of his house to receive guests/travellers, and be able to teach/advise other people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patao-palaha boe = ; pasue toke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">patao-palaha boe = ; pasue toke madhe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="anepilemptos: irreproachable, above reproach, blameless nephalios:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">anepilemptos: irreproachable, above reproach, blameless nephalios: temperate in the use of wine, sober<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>swphron: prudent, sensible, thoughtful, self-controlled kosmios: respectable, dignified, honorable<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>philoxenos: hospitable, friend of strangers didaktikos: skillful in teaching<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: A bishop must be blameless, the husband of one wife, sober, self-controlled, respectable, hospitable, a good teacher,</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Baku dhèu dhu tema mahu, baku dhèu dhu nasa dènge kacui-aai malai. Dhu lèke ka, dhèu dhu d'ara hua iia, dhu d'èi tenge dame, aa dhu manga'a boe doi-dhari.<bt>It shouldn't be someone who is a drunkard (&lt; often drunk), and shouldn't be someone who is quickly angered and violent. The best (character) match is someone who has a beautiful inside/character (Idiom = gracious), who likes to be a peace-maker, and who is not greedy for money.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manga'a = rakus ; nasa malai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">manga'a = rakus ; nasa malai = broad, can be with words only ; kacui-aai malai = 1) quickly violent, 2) sticky fingers</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paroinos: drunken, addicted to wine, alcoholic"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paroinos: drunken, addicted to wine, alcoholic plekte: bully, violent, fist-fighter<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>epeieikes: gentle, yielding, kind, mild hamaxos: not quarrelsome, not argumentative<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>aphilarguros: not greedy, not loving money LITERALLY: not drunken, not violent, but gentle, not argumentative, not greedy for money,<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Nèngu hud'i ne'a uri d'ara èmu na dènge be'a. Ana-ana na re'a pakab'ua dènge d'èi nanene ne.<bt>S/He must be able to manage1/organise/look after his own family/household well. His children must respect and listen/obey him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalws: well proistemi: manage, conduct, administer,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kalws: well proistemi: manage, conduct, administer, rule<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>hupotage: submission, subjection, obedience semnotetos: reverence, respectful (translated as if it belonged with hypotageei, but could go with ekhonta).<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>LITERALLY: managing his own household well, having children in obedience with all respectfulness;</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ladhe dhèu èèna ne'a boe lalau-lalo'o d'ara èmu na, na, tasa mera mia nèngu bisa ladhe-leru juma'at Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if that person can't manage2/look after his own household, na, how can he be able to manage1 the Lord's congregation?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Baku dhèu dhu tema mahu,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">Diperhatikan: Baku dhèu dhu tema mahu, baku dhèu dhu kacuiai malai atau kacuiaai. Apakah aa dua atau a 1saja.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epimeleomai: care for. LITERALLY: (for if"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">epimeleomai: care for. LITERALLY: (for if anyone does not know how to manage his own household, how can he care for the church of God?)<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Be'a risi, pili dhèu dhu mamuri palèke dènge dad'èi Kristus. De baku ded'e kètu juma'at nèti dhèu dhu parcaya nèbhu mèka mi Yesus. Te èèna na, rèngu sèra bisa padedha iisi malai. Mage dhoka Lamatua huku si, sama sèmi Lamatua huku dhèu aae nidhu.<bt>It is best/better to choose a person who is already mature/adult in/matching Kristus' will. So don't elevate/install the head-leader of the congregation from people who have not long believed in Yesus. Cuz (elaboration) it's easy for them to become proud/arrogant. Lest the Lord punish them, like the Lord punishes the *devil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palèke ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">palèke =</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neophutos: recent convert, newcomer tuphow: puffed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">neophutos: recent convert, newcomer tuphow: puffed up, conceited, haughty, arrogant and foolish, proud<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>krima: judgment, condemnation empiptw: fall into<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>LITERALLY: not a recent convert, lest he become puffed up and fall into the condemnation of the Devil.</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dhèu dhu j'aj'i kètu juma'at sèra hud'i dhèu dhu rai lesa re'a pakab'ua ne kahèi. Dènge sèmi èèna nèngu makae boe. Aa dhèu aae nidhu bisa boe pabèbhe ne kahèi.<bt>A person who becomes the head-leader of congregation(s) must be a person whom outsiders know how to respect also. In that way he won't be ashamed/embarrassed. And the *devil cannot cause him to fall (socially, morally) either.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai lesa = masyarakat umum ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">rai lesa = masyarakat umum ; pabhèbhe = kasi jato</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marturia: testimony, witness kalos: good|i(7) (7)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">marturia: testimony, witness kalos: good<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>ekswthen: outside oneidismos: reproach, reviling, disgrace, abuse<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>empiptw: fall pagis: trap, snare<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>LITERALLY: But it is necessary for him to have a good testimony from outsiders, so he may not fall into disgrace and the trap of the Devil.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:2-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Titus 1:6-9</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu soru-bara kètu juma'at<bt>People who assist (play second) to the head-leader of congregations</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu soru-bara kètu juma'at. Rèngu sèra hud'i dhèu dhu dènge kolongara be'a, dhèu dhu he'o kajari boe, dhu tema boe rinu mahu, aa dhu d'èi boe ra'e a'oto ae-ae.<bt>It is the same way also with people who assist the head-leader(s) of congregation(s). They must be people who have a good name/reputation, people who are not gossips (lit. forked tongue, saying different things to different people), who do not normally drink themselves drunk, and who do not like to eat/consume excessive profit.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soru-bara = terima untuk numpang, ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">soru-bara = terima untuk numpang, ; soru = jemput ; bara = wakil, bantu ; he'o kajari boe = lidah tidak bacabang, not gossip, say different things to different people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="TERM: Use this as the model"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">TERM: Use this as the model for the parallel part of Titus (1:6-7) diakonos: deacon as a subordinate officer of the church, servant, minister, servant in a menial capacity, servant who sacrifices himself<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>semnos: serious, dignified, noble, person worthy of respect, worthy, soberminded. Titus 1:7 and 1 Tim 2:2 are the model for this. dilogos: double-tongued, insincere, not straightforward, not truthful, hypocritical, deceitful<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>prosexw: addicted, occupy oneself with, devoted to aisxrokerdeis: greedy for dishonest gain, moneygrubbing<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: Deacons likewise serious, not insincere, not addicted to much wine, not greedy for dishonest gain,</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />D'ara rèngu hud'i mola-mèci, aa rèngu hud'i kèpe pa'èra ku Lii Holo-Nori dhu Lamatua bhoke pasaraa hia èdhi, dhèu parcaya se'e.<bt>Their insides must be pure/clean, and they must hold firmly to the Gospel which the Lord has revealed to us-inc believers.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="musterion: mystery, secret, secret rite, secret"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">musterion: mystery, secret, secret rite, secret teaching, hidden thing katharos: clear, pure<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>suneidesis: conscience, moral consciousness LITERALLY: holding the mystery of the faith with a good conscience.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ladhe paie-iie mamuri dènge sasab'a ra. Ladhe abhu boe sasala si, heka ded'e si ho soru-bara kètu juma'at sèra.<bt>Examine carefully their life and work. If (you) find none of their wrongs, na, only then elevate them to assist those head(s) of congregation(s).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dokimazw: put to the test, test,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">dokimazw: put to the test, test, examine eita: then<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>diakoneitw: serve as a deacon anegkletos: blameless, irreproachable, guiltless, without stain<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>LITERALLY: But let them be tested first, then if they are blameless, let them serve as a deacon.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu èmu ra. Rèngu sèra hud'i bhèni dhu mamuri madhutu madha j'ara dènge tatao dhu be'a. Mage dhèu dhu tema padhai-kakoli pa'ele iie kolongara dhèu leo. Rèngu hud'i dhèu dhu re'a taha rare d'ara, aa dhèu lèka si kahèi.<bt>It is the same also with their spouses. They must be women who live according to the ways and behaviour which are good. They should not be people who often slander ruining other people's names/reputations. They must be people who know how to restrain/control themselves, and people also trust them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhai-kakoli = omong bekin busuk nama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">padhai-kakoli = omong bekin busuk nama</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Diperhatikan: Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèuèmu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">Diperhatikan: Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèuèmu ra. Apakah penulisan nya begini atau ada perubahan.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Aa dhu soru-bara kètu juma'at sèra hud'i mone dhu satia dènge dhèu èmu na ca dhèu di. Nèngu èèna hud'i ne'a uri d'ara èmu na, aa uri ana-ana na dènge be'a.<bt>And those who assist heads of congregations must be men who are faithful with their one spouse. S/He must know how to manage1/look after his own household, and his children well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="proistemi: manage, lead LITERALLY: Let deacons"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">proistemi: manage, lead LITERALLY: Let deacons be the husband of one wife, managing their children and their own household well;<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Rèngu dhu lalau-lalo'o dhèu sarani dènge be'a, tatu dhèu asa pakab'ua si. Aa rèngu asa bani, dènge boe madha'u lole parcaya rèngu mi Yesus Kristus.<bt>Those who manage2/serve Christians well, surely people will increasingly honour/respect them. And they will become more bold, and not be afraid to tell about their faith in Yesus Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bathmos: step, grade, rank, standing, status"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">bathmos: step, grade, rank, standing, status peripoiew: gain, acquire, obtain<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: For those who serve well as deacons win for themselves a good status and much boldness in the faith in Christ Jesus.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kapua nèti lalèka èdhi<bt>The base/source/foundation of our-inc faith</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14-15" />Timotius! Ja'a sanao sèna ka nèbhu boe ja'a dhiu ngad'o èu. Ladhe ja'a pakai, do ako nena ciki, na, ele boe sasuri ne d'ai uuru èu. Sasuri ne ja'a suri ho peka dènge èu, na, dhèu unu Lamatua sèra hud'i ra mamuri tasa mera mia ku. Baku bhèlu, peka na, Lamatua èèna, Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri. Dhèu unu Na nuka sèmi èmu dhu dènge era padhèdi, aa dènge agarii talora dhu èra. Èmu sèmi èèna ka dhu titu èra, sama sèmi dhèu unu Lamatua dhu kèpe pa'èra Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dhu tare'a, aa rèngu bisa bara ho pakako dènge be'a.<bt>Timotius! I hope that soon, I will stop and visit you. If I get blocked, or delayed a little, this letter will probably arrive first to you. This letter I write to tell you how the Lord's children must live. Don't forget that the Lord is the Father God who lives. His people are like a house with a foundation, and with a strong central post. A house like that stands strongly, is like God1's people who hold firmly God's true Word, and they can assist to carry it out well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèni = dasar, fondasi, (but H"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">kèni = dasar, fondasi, (but H not know) ; pakai = ga'e, halangan ; bara = bantu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, rèngu sèra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, rèngu sèra bisa bara, dara pakako lii holo nori Ama Lamatua dhu tare'a.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Lamatua pasabhoka le rahasia dhu kapai nèti lalèka èdhi. Kapua na sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>The Lord has revealed the great secret (loan) about our-inc faith. It's basis is like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasabhoka = kasi tabuka, beberkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pasabhoka = kasi tabuka, beberkan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Kristus èèna, ca Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>Kristus is a person whom Father God set apart from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Kristus èèna mai le asa rai-haha ne, pake rupa dhèu rai-haha sèmi èdhi.<bt>And that Kristus has come to this earth using the form of a human like us-inc.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Roh Lamatua ka dhu j'aj'i sakasii, peka na, Yesus èèna, nuka Kristus.<bt>The Spirit of God is the one who is a witness, that that Yesus, is the Kristus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ana pajuu Lamatua ètu sorga sèra rèdhi Na kahèi.<bt>And the servants of the Lord in heaven also see Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ama Lamatua dhu ded'e nèti le asa sorga,<bt>Father God has taken Him up to heaven,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka nedhe padedha-dedha Ne.<bt>and elevated Him on high.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lii Lolo Na pale-lème le suku-suku ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>His Story has already spread to various tribes/ethnic groups on this earth.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ètu mia-mia ètu rai-haha ne, dhèu aa'i-aa'i parcaya le Nèngu.<bt>Everywhere in this world all (hyperbole) people already believe in Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Kapua lalèka èdhi sèmi èèna ka!<bt>That is the basis of our faith!</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Baku pamud'e dènge dhèu dhu aj'a pakapod'e dhèu sarani<bt>Be careful with people who teach chaos/confusion to Christians</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Te ngaa ne'e ne, Roh Ama Lamatua dhu peka paled'a le, na, bèli-camèd'a dhèu sarani cahag'e patalale eele ngaa dhu èdhi parcaya. Ho lasi madhutu roh-roh dhu sala aa dhu leko-monya, aa lasi madhutu lii holo-nori nidhu bhelu sèra.<bt>But now Father God's Spirit has made known very clearly that later some Christians will reject/throw away what we-inc believe. So they will go off and follow/obey various spirits which deceive making humans lost, and go follow the teaching of demons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paled'a = pasabhoka, terbuka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">paled'a = pasabhoka, terbuka</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pneuma: spirit hretos: expressly, explicitly, specifically|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pneuma: spirit hretos: expressly, explicitly, specifically<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>legw: say husteros: latter, later, last<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>kairos: time aphistemi: fall away, depart, remove themselves<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>pistis: faith, what is believed prosexw: pay attention to, give heed to, follow<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>planos: deceitful, seductive didaskalia: teaching, doctrine<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>daimonion: demon, evil spirit LITERALLY: But the Spirit says specifically that in later times certain ones will depart from the faith, paying attention to deceitful spirits and teachings of demons,<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Dhèu dhu mai nori sèmi sèra, padhai lii leo, tao leo. Dhèu sèra mema dhèu dhu kapod'e-kabèli! Dhèu sèra sa, d'ara iiki ra dhu bèdhu le.<bt>People who come teaching like that, they say one thing and do another. They are fundamentally deceivers/cheaters/swindlers! Their consciences are blind/dull.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhèdu = buta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">bhèdu = buta</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hupokrisis: hypocrisy, pretense, outward show pseudologos:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hupokrisis: hypocrisy, pretense, outward show pseudologos: liar, false speaker<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>kausteriazw: sear, cauterize, burn into insensitivity idios: one's own<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>suneidesis: conscience, moral consciousness LITERALLY: in hypocrisy of liars, having their own consciences seared,<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Ra aj'a dhèu, baku paleo èmu. Aa ra aj'a dhèu luri rupa-rupa nganga'a. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua ka dhu tao nganga'a-nganginu sèra, ho ladhe dhèu parcaya ra'a, rèngu manèngi makasi mi Nèngu. Te rèngu re'a mia dhu lèke.<bt>They teach people to not marry. And they teach people to make taboo various sorts of food. But Father God is the one who made those foods (doublet), so that when believers eat, na, they give thanks to Him. Cuz (elaboration) they know what's right/true/correct!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ra aj'a dhèu, baku paleo èmu."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">Ra aj'a dhèu, baku paleo èmu. Aa ra aj'a dhèu luri rupa-rupa nganga'a. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua ka dhu tao nganga'a-nganginu sèra. De ladhe dhèu parcaya ra'a, rèngu manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Rèngu re'a mia dhu lèke.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kwluw: hinder, forbid, prohibit gamew: marry|i(3)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kwluw: hinder, forbid, prohibit gamew: marry<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>apexw: keep away, abstain brwma: food<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ktizw: create metalempsis: receive<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>euxaristia: thanksgiving pistis: faith, belief<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>epiginwskw: know aletheia: truth<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>LITERALLY: forbidding to marry, keeping away from foods which God created for receiving with thanksgiving by those who believe and know the truth.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua tao sèra, tare'a-re'a be'a. De baku luri rupa-rupa. Dhèu hud'i sèmi rare aa'i-aa'i sèra dènge manèngi makasi mi Lamatua.<bt>Everything that Father God has done/made, is truly good. So don't make various taboos (thoughtlessly)! People should accept all of it and give thanks to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luri = vt"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">luri = vt</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pas: all, everything ktisma: creation, creature|i(4)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pas: all, everything ktisma: creation, creature<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>kalos: good apobletos: rejected, refused, thrown away, taboo<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>lambanw: receive, take, grasp, take hold of, get, obtain LITERALLY: Because every creation of God is good, and nothing to be rejected if it is received with thanksgiving,<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te èdhi te'a, na, Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua dènge lii manèngi-mangaj'i èdhi sèra ka pamèu si.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) we-inc know that Father God's Words/Message, and our-inc prayers, are what make them be/become clean/pure.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagiazw: sanctify, consecrate, dedicate, set apart"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hagiazw: sanctify, consecrate, dedicate, set apart fo God, make holy logos: word<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>enteuksews: prayer LITERALLY: for it is sanctified through the word of God and prayer.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu sab'a dhu be'a nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>A good worker of the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Timotius! Pasanèd'e j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i mi a'ari èdhi dhèu parcaya sèra. Ladhe èu tao madhutu sèmi èèna, èu j'aj'i dhèu sab'a dhu be'a nèti Yesus Kristus. Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua sèra ka dhu tao èu parcaya Ne, aa hia me'a mèu, mia ka lii holo-nori dhu lèke. Èu kèpe pa'èra-èra le Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua sèra! Sèra nuka sèmi nganga'a dhu pa'èra ngi'u èu.<bt>Timotius! Remind our fellow (elder-younger sibling) believers of all these things. If/when you-sg do that, you are a good worker of Yesus Kristus. Father God's Words made you (to) believe in Him, and made/allowed you to understand which teachings are true/corect. You have been holding firmly to God's Words! They are just like food that gives strength to your body.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hupotithemi: suggest, point out something, make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hupotithemi: suggest, point out something, make known, show, remind adelphos: brother<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>kalos: good diakonos: servant, minister, helper<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>entrephw: bring up, nourish, rear as a child, train logos: word<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>pistis: faith didaskalia: teaching<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>parakolouthew: follow, attend to a course of instruction LITERALLY: Reminding the brothers of these things, you will be a good servant of Christ Jesus, being nourished by the words of faith, an of the good teaching which you have followed;<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Baku core eele lod'o iia d'ara dènge palolo omo koso dhu lèke boe dènge dad'èi Ama Lamatua. Baku pusi-pahae dènge lii lolo bhèni heka dhu nèti laluri rupa-rupa. Be'a risi pa'èra taruu ngi'u dènge d'ara èu pabe'a-be'a, sèna ka mamuri madhutu dad'èi Lamatua ètu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Don't waste time with pointless stories that have no connection with Father God's will. Don't pay any attention to the old women's tales explaining various taboos. It is better for you to keep strengthening your body/self (?) and insides well/carefully so that you live according to God's will in all matters.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bebelos: profane, godless grawdes: like an"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">bebelos: profane, godless grawdes: like an old woman, silly, foolish, frivolous, absurd, senseless<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>muthos: fable, myth, tale, story, legend paraiteomai: refuse, reject, avoid, have nothing to do with<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>gumnazw: train, exercise seautos: yourself<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>eusebeia: godliness, religion, piety LITERALLY: but refuse godless and silly stories, and train yourself in godliness;<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Olaraga pa'èra ngi'u na, be'a.<bt>Doing sports (loan) which strengthen your body/self is good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhori = tali ; bhori pa'èra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">bhori = tali ; bhori pa'èra = encircle like a weight belt to give strength.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Masi ka babe'a na ciki oo'e di.<bt>But it is only useful a little bit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te ngaa pa'èra ngi'u dènge d'ara ho mamuri madhutu dad'èi Lamatua ètu j'ara aa'i-aa'i sèra,<bt>But strengthen your body/self and insides to live according to God's will in all matters,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">babe'a na ae seli eele.<bt>it has many uses/is useful for many things.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Babe'a na<bt>It is good</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">mesa boe mamuri ètu rai-haha deo ne'e di,<bt>not only for life in this world now,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te ngaa mamuri lèpa limuri kahèi.<bt>but also for life that is coming later.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="swmatikos: bodily gumnasia: training, exercise|i(8) (8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">swmatikos: bodily gumnasia: training, exercise<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>oligos: little, a little, some wphelimos: useful, beneficial, advantageous<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>eusebeia: godliness, piety, religion epaggelia: promise, offer, pledge<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>exw: have zwe: life<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>nun: now, present mellw: to be destined, to come<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: for bodily exercise is profitable for a little, butt godliness is profitable for all things, having promise of life now and to come.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Lii se'e se, lèke tare'a-re'a! De tèke paie mi d'ara, ho baku bhèlu eele.<bt>These words are true/correct! So store/save/place them away in your insides so you don't forget.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pistos: faith, faithful, trustworthy, sure logos:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pistos: faith, faithful, trustworthy, sure logos: word, saying<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>pas: all, full apodoxes: acceptance, approval<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>aksios: worthy, deserving LITERALLY: The saying is trustworthy and deserving of full acceptance;<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Èdhi tao era maena mi Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri. Nèngu na ka dhu hia mamuri mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i, risi-risi mi èdhi dhu parcaya Na. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi sab'a dènge d'ara kateme.<bt>[EXEG: he is Saviour of all, but even in 1 Tim, that does not mean that all are saved. so Saviour of all is taken in the weak sense, not the strong sense] We-inc keep placing our hope in Father God who lives. He is the one who gives (~makes available) life/salvation to everyone, especially to those of us-inc who believe in Him. That is why we-inc work wholeheartedly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kopiaw: toil, become weary, labor, work"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kopiaw: toil, become weary, labor, work hard agwnizomai: struggle, strive, fight<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>elpizw: hope zaw: live<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>swter: savior malista: above all, especially<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>pistos: faith LITERALLY: toward which we work hard and struggle, because we hope on the living God, who is the savior of all men, especially of the ones that believe.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Nori lii se'e aa'i-aa'i. Aa pua dhèu sèra ho madhutu lii holo-nori sèra.<bt>Teach all these things. And order/tell people to follow/obey these teachings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paraggellw: give orders, command didaskw: teach|i(11)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paraggellw: give orders, command didaskw: teach<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>LITERALLY: Command and teach these things.</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Baku soro tèka dhèu sèra pahae boe èu, lula èu ana ngèru era. Èu hud'i j'aj'i conto hia dhèu parcaya sèra, nèti lii padhai èu, nèti kakako èu, nèti d'ara sasue èu mi dedha dhèu, nèti parcaya èu mi Yesus Kristus, dènge mamuri èu dhu mola-mèci.<bt>Don't let people to look down on/scorn/disparage you because you are still young. You-sg must be an example for the believers, from what you say, your behaviour, the way you love people, your faith/belief in Yesus Kristus, and your clean/pure life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="medeis: no veotes: youth|i(12) (12) |rkataphronew:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">medeis: no veotes: youth<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>kataphronew: scorn, despise tupos: mark, example, pattern<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>ginomai: become, be pistos: trustworthy<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>logos: word, speech anastpophhe: conduct, way of life<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>agape: love pistis: faith, trust, confidence<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>hagneia: purity, moral cleanness LITERALLY: Don't let anyone scorn your youth, but be a model for those who believe in word, in conduct, in love, in faith, in purity.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ètu d'ara miu tatae mamai ja'a, baku bhèlu baca Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua hia mi dhèu parcaya sèra. Pa'èra d'ara si, aa nori si paie-iie.<bt>While you-pl are waiting for my coming, don't forget to read God's Words to the believers. Strengthen/encourage them, and teach them well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hews: until erxomai: come|i(13) (13) |rprosexw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hews: until erxomai: come<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>prosexw: pay attention to, devote yourself to, occupy yourself with anagnwsis: reading, public reading<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>paraklesis: encouragement, exhortation, preaching didaskalia: teaching, doctrine<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: Until I come pay attention to the public reading, to preaching, to the teaching.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Pake pabe'a-be'a karunya dhu Lamatua pangèd'u le mi èu, dhu èu sèmi lod'o kètu-kètu juma'at sabaj'a dènge tao kacui-aai mi dedha kètu èu. Lod'o èèna, rèngu peka lii moa Lamatua kahèi lula-nèti j'ara mamuri dènge sab'a-la'a èu. De baku soro tèke karunya dhu èu abhu èèna.<bt>Use well the *gift/ability.from.above (loan) which God has given/entrusted to you-sg, which you received when the heads-leaders of the congregation(s) prayed and placed their hands on your head. At that time, they also made known God's message/instructions about your life and work. So, don't let it lie the gift that you have.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karunia = dhu abhu iia dara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">karunia = dhu abhu iia dara nèti Lamatua ; soro tèke = dibiarkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="amelew: neglect, leave, lack of attention"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">amelew: neglect, leave, lack of attention xarisma: a gift<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>didwmi: give propheteia: prophecy<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>epithesis: laying on xeirwn: hand<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>presbuterion: council of elders LITERALLY: Do not neglect the gift in you, which was given you through prophecy with the laying on of hands by the elders.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Pakako dènge maj'èni j'ara sèra. Sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra ladhe rèdhi mamuri dènge sab'a-la'a èu asa be'a.<bt>Carry out those matters with diligence/industriousness. So that everyone see that your life and work are good.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meletaw: practise eimi: be|i(15) (15) |rprokope:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">meletaw: practise eimi: be<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>prokope: progress phaneros: clear<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>pas: all LITERALLY: Practise these things, give yourself to them, that your progress may be seen by everyone.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="16" />J'aga sèna ka èu mamuri dènge mola. Aa j'aga sèna ka èu loe boe aj'a dhu lèke j'ara. Ladhe èu pa'èra dènge j'ara sèra, pe Lamatua bhoke j'ara hia èu, dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu nanene lii padhai èu, sèna ka miu pakaj'èu nèti bhabhelu-katub'a.<bt>Take care that you-sg live straight/righteous/just. And take care that you always teach what is right/correct. If/when you are strong/persevere with all that, then God will open the way for you and the people who listen to what you say, so that you-pl can be freed/released/spared from evil/bad things. [EXEG/ Key Term: HCE: while Knight and others argue for a "soterilogical (spiritual) salvation" here, TN and TH discuss significant complexities/problems with that, and TH gives an alternate translation similar to above. Carlton also adds object to "saved (from eternal destruction)". The complications with going literal for Kupang and surrounding lgs is 1) it implies Timothy is not yet saved (addressed at length in TN, but without saying how to handle it, and still a problem for KM), and 2) saying that Timothy can save himself (which the Gk does say, but it creates significant worldview/lexical clashes here (similar to a human cannot "bless" God). So here, to not introduce error and misunderstandings, we have had to go Specific -- Generic, using /swzw/ meaning of "preserve, keep from harm" (LN, BAGD), which is adequate for the context and much less problematic for KM.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epexw: aim at, pay attention to,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">epexw: aim at, pay attention to, keep a close watch on, hold to seautou: yourself<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>didaskalia: teaching, doctrine epimenw: continue, remain, persist, stick to, cling to<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>poiew: do swzw: save, rescue (from danger, destruction), preserve, keep from harm<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>akouw: hear LITERALLY: Keep a close watch on yourself and the teaching; continue in them; for by doing this you will save yourself and those who hear you.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tatao Timotius mi dhèu sarani<bt>Advice for our behaviour toward Christians</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Baku tao lii sakaa dènge dhèu mone dhu heka risi nèti èu. Te ngaa dènge lii mako, nuka sèmi èu padhai lii dènge ama mu. Aa mi dhèu dhu ngèru risi, pa'èra d'ara si, tao nuka sèmi ari mu.<bt>Don't scold/reprimand men who are older than you-sg using a loud/harsh voice. But use language that is sweet (=polite, attractive, positive), just like you would use with your (own) father. And with people who are younger, encourage/inspire/enthuse them, just as if they are your own sibling.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii sakaa = suara keras"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">lii sakaa = suara keras</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="presbuteros: elder, older man epiplessw: rebuke,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">presbuteros: elder, older man epiplessw: rebuke, reprove, scold, bawl out, strike at (strong)<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>parakalew: exhort, appeal to, urge, encourage, console, conciliate, speak to in a friendly manner, admonish, comfort, call aside newteros: younger man<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>LITERALLY: Do not scold an older man, but appeal to him as a father, young men as brothers,</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Sèmi èèna kahèi mi dhèu bhèni dhu heka risi sèra. Padhai lii dènge rèngu, nuka sèmi èu padhai lii dènge ina mu. Aa ladhe padhai lii dènge ana bhèni ngèru, tao si nuka sèmi ana hèni èu. D'ara èu hud'i mola dènge si.<bt>It is the same with women who are older. Speak to them just as you would speak to your (own) mother. If you speak with women who are younger, treat them just like your own sister. Your insides must be clean/pure with them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hagneia: purity, moral purity, chastity, blamelessness"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hagneia: purity, moral purity, chastity, blamelessness LITERALLY: older women as mothers, younger women as sisters in all purity.<span class="Italic">(2)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Bhèni balu<bt>About/concerning widows</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3-5" />Dhèu sarani hud'i soru-bara bhèni balu dhu dènge heka a'ari sèna ka ladhe-leru si. Te ngaa bhèni balu dhu ana-èpu era, na, rèngu ka dhu hud'i ladhe-leru ne. Aj'a si, sèna ka re'a b'ala sasue ina ra dhu rèngu abhu sèra. Dènge sèmi èèna ka, rèngu sab'a hia Ama Lamatua, ho pakarej'e d'ara Na. Te ngaa bhèni balu dhu tare'a-re'a mamuri mesa di, nèngu dènge boe ca dhèu sa dhu ladhe-leru ne. Nèngu dhoka maena mi Ama Lamatua di. Mèu-mèda na manèngi sasue Ama Lamatua. Dhèu sarani hud'i ladhe-leru ku bhèni balu sèmi sèra sa.<bt>Christians must help/assist widow ladies, who don't have any family/kin who can take care of/look after them any more. But as for widows who still have children-grandchildren, they are the ones who must take care of her. Teach them, so they know/are able to repay/reciprocate her love for them which they have received/obtained. In that way they work for Father God, to please His insides. But (as for) widows who truly live alone, she doesn't have anyone else to take care of her. She only hopes in God alone. Day-night (=constantly) she prays asking for help/love/pity/mercy from God. Christians must/should take care of widows of that sort.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="xeras: widow timaw: honor, revere, respect,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">xeras: widow timaw: honor, revere, respect, material support<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>LITERALLY: Honor widows that are really widows. teknon: child<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>ekgonos: grandchild manthanw: learn<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>prwton: first oikos: household, family<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>eusebew: be reverent, respectful, honor, devout, pious, religious duty amoibas: return, repayment<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>apodidomi: reward, make a return, repay progonos: parent<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>apodektos: acceptable, pleasing LITERALLY: But if any widow has children or grandchildren, let them learn first to show godly honor to their own family and repay their parents, for this is pleasing before God.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>monow: be left alone, solitary elpizw: set hope on<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>prosmenw: continue deesis: prayer, entreaty, pleading, request<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>proseuxe: general prayer LITERALLY: But the widow who is alone sets her hope on God, and continues in requests and prayers night and day;<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa bhèni balu dhu d'èi dhoka mamuri na karej'e-karae di, masi ka na mamuri era, te ngaa dènge heka kab'ua, sama sèmi dhèu dhu madhe le.<bt>But (as for) widows who just like to live happily (or for their own pleasure), even though she still lives, nevertheless she has no more value, like a person who has already died.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="spatalaw: live luxuriously or voluptuously, indulge,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">spatalaw: live luxuriously or voluptuously, indulge, give self to pleasure, indulge freely in eating and drinking, yield to the appetites zaw: live<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>thneskw: die LITERALLY: But the one who gives herself to pleasure is dead while she is living.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Pasanèd'e j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i mi dhèu sarani sèra, sèna ka dhèu leo baku pa'ele iie kolongara rèngu.<bt>Remind the Christians of all these things, so that outsiders cannot speak causing damage to their name/reputation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paraggellw: command, direct, urge, insist on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paraggellw: command, direct, urge, insist on anepilemptos: be without reproach, irreproachable, blameless<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>LITERALLY: Command these things, so that they may be blameless.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Aa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu ro'o boe ladhe-leru a'ari na, risi-risi hari isi èmu na, èèna sama sèmi nèngu pèci eele lalèka nèngu mi Lamatua. Nèngu bhelu risi nèti dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>And if there are people who don't want to take care of their own family/kin, especially (from) his/her own family members, that is just like s/he has thrown away/discarded his/her faith/belief in God. S/he is more evil than people who don't know/recognise God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pronoew: think of beforehand, take care,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">pronoew: think of beforehand, take care, provide arneomai: deny, repudiate, disown<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>apistos: faithless, unbelieving xeipwn: worse<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: But if anyone does not provide for his own, and especially his own household, he has denied the faith and is worse than an unbeliever.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ladhe neo ded'e bhèni balu ho soru-bara kètu juma'at, j'ara na sèmi ne'e ka: umur nèngu bisa boe kura nèti 60 tèu; uru na nèngu satia dènge dhèu èmu na ca dhèu di;<bt>If you want to elevate/appoint/install a widow to assist/help the leaders of the congregation, the way/requirements/qualifications are like this: her age shouldn't be below 60 years old; formerly she should have lived faithfully/loyally with just one husband;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="katalegw: select, enroll elatton: less|i(9) (9)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">katalegw: select, enroll elatton: less<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>etos: year heksekonta: sixty<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>gune: heis: one<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>LITERALLY: Enroll widows not less than sixty years old, the wife of one husband,</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />dhèu re'a, na, nèngu ca dhèu dhu tema tao babe'a mi dhèu; dhu ladhe-leru ana-ana na dènge be'a; dhu bhoke tèke kacui-aai ho leru dhèu leo; dhu soru-bara dhèu parcaya sèra ètu d'ara sasab'a, masi ka dhu samaa èèna ka; dhu d'èi soru dhèu ètu d'ara sasusa; aa dhu bhori mema ho soru-bara ètu madha j'ara dhu be'a.<bt>people know/recognise her as a person who is characterised by doing good things to/for other people; as one who took good care of her own children; as one who opened her hands (=willingly) to serve other people; as one who makes herself useful/does whatever is need to help believers in even the small/unimportant/light/insignificant things; as one who likes to/often help people who are in difficulty; and as one who is always ready to help with good/worthy things.[CHECK /soru/ with UNS]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakabèle = open both hands ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pakabèle = open both hands ; samaa = ringan ; soru = menyambut ; tuntut ; bhori mema = always ready ; Soru CIE with soro</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marturew: be well spoken of, testified"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">marturew: be well spoken of, testified about teknotrophew: nourishing children, bring up children<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>ksenodoxew: show hospitality to strangers thlibw: oppress, afflict<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>eparkew: help, relieve, aid hagios: saints<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>pous foot niptw: wash<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>epakolouthew: follow after, devote self to LITERALLY: having a testimony of good works, if she has brought up children, if she has been hospitable to strangers, if she has washed the feet of the saints, if she has helped the troubled, if she has devoted herself to every good work.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Baku pili bhèni balu dhu ngèru era, ho sab'a ètu d'ara juma'at. Te mage dhoka cèu ètu d'ara na, ho neo hari leo-èmu. Ladhe sèmi èèna, rèngu se abhu heka lod'o dhu taleo, ho lalau dhèu sarani dènge be'a.<bt>Don't take widows who are still young to work in the congregation. Lest arises in thier insides, so they want to get married again. In that way, they don't have any more opportunity to serve the Christians well. [CHECK second sentence, if sexual desires are clear with these prudes :-).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paraitew: refuse katastreniazw: [young ox] trying"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paraitew: refuse katastreniazw: [young ox] trying to escape from the yoke, exercise youthful vigor against, be restless against, resist<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>LITERALLY: But refuse to enroll younger widows, for whenever they exercise youthful vigor against Christ, they desire to marry,</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Te ladhe lod'o dhu rèngu pake hia juma'at èèna kura, èci èèna ka dènge rèngu pa'ele iie lii pajaji rèngu ètu katanga madha Lamatua. Èèna na, dhèu pasala si.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if/when their time available to the congregation diminishes, that is the same as if they have broken their promise before God. Then people will blame/accuse them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="atheteo: declare invalid, nullify, set aside,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">atheteo: declare invalid, nullify, set aside, break a pledge LITERALLY: bringing condemnation on themselves because they have set aside their first promise<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Mage dhoka rèngu bai-eed'a, aa maso-kalua èmu dhèu, padhai-kaked'u pa'ele iie kolongara dhèu. Aa dhu karehe risi eele hari, rèngu soro iisi asa d'ara lii langu dhèu leo, dènge padhai dhu lèke boe.<bt>It would not be good if they were lazy, and then go in-out of people's houses, telling foolish/nonsense/pointless tales [that] damage people's name/reputation. And what is even worse, they [would] like/tend to butt in/involve themselves in other people's matters/disputes, and say things that are not appropriate/true.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ridu = terjun ; padhai-kaked'u ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">ridu = terjun ; padhai-kaked'u = (1 UNS doesn't know kaked'u)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hama: together argos: idle|i(13) (13) |rmanthanw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hama: together argos: idle<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>manthanw: learn perierxomai: go around<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>phluaros: gossipy periergos: meddlesome<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>lalew: speak dei: it is necessary<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: Besides, they learn to be lazy, going around the houses, and not only lazy, but gossipy and meddlesome, talking about what they shouldn't.</Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Be'a risi eele, bhèni balu dhu ngèru era leo hari èmu, sèna ka rara iisi, aa ladhe-leru d'ara èmu rèngu. Dènge sèmi èèna, dhèu dhu pamusu dènge èdhi abhu boe j'ara ho pa'ele iie kolongara èdhi.<bt>It would be better for widows who are still young to marry again, so they can have children (lit. give birth), and manage their own household. In that way, people who are hostile to/oppose us-inc have no reason/excuse to make rotten our-inc name/reputation.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boulomai: desire tekvogonew: bear children|i(14) (14)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">boulomai: desire tekvogonew: bear children<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>oikodespotew: manage household medeis: no<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>aphorme: pretext, reason antikeimai: be opposed, oppose. Could refer to the Devil, or to any opponent<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>loidoria: abuse, revile xarin: for the sake of, on account of, because of<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>LITERALLY: I desire therefore younger widows to marry, to bear children, to manage their households, to not give the opponent a reason to revile;</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Abhu bhèni balu ngèru cahag'e dhu kako sala j'ara. Rèngu se madhutu j'ara dhèu aae nidhu.<bt>There are some young widows who have already lost their way. They are following/obeying the way/path of the *devil.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ektrepw: turn away, turn, stray, swerve"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">ektrepw: turn away, turn, stray, swerve opisw: after<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>Satanaa: da Devil LITERALLY: for already some have turned away after Satan.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ladhe abhu bhèni dhu parcaya Lamatua, dhu a'ari ra j'aj'i le bhèni balu, na, bhèni ne hud'i ladhe-leru ku bhèni balu èèna. Baku soro tèke hia juma'at ladhe-leru. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna juma'at bisa ladhe-leru bhèni balu dhu leo, dhu tare'a-re'a dènge heka a'ari.<bt>If there is a woman who believes in God, whose family/kin has become a widow, na, that woman must help/assist that widow. Don't let/allow the congregation to look after her. In that way, the congregation can help other widows, who really have no other kin.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eparkeitw: help, aid barew: burden, weigh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">eparkeitw: help, aid barew: burden, weigh down<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>ekklesia: church, congregation ontws: real<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>LITERALLY: If any believing woman has widows, let her help them, and let not the church be burdened, so that they may help the real widows.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tatao dhu pakab'ua kètu juma'at<bt>Ways that honour leaders of the congregation(s)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Dhèu dhu ladhe-leru juma'at dènge be'a, miu hud'i pakab'ua risi ne, aa b'ae gaji dènge be'a. Risi-risi rèngu dhu sab'a dènge d'ara kateme, ho lole pataraa Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua, aa aj'a j'ara mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>(As for) people who lead the congregation(s) well, you-pl must give more honour/respect to him/her and pay him/her a true/correct/appropriate wage. Especially those who work wholeheartedly to explain God's Words, and teach you-pl the true/correct way of life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalws: well proistemi: rule, manage, conduct,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kalws: well proistemi: rule, manage, conduct, administer, lead<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>diplous: double time: honor, compensation, remuneration<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>aksiow: consider worthy kopiaw: become weary, work hard, labor<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>LITERALLY: The elders who rule well are worthy of double honor, especially the ones who work hard in the word and teaching;</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Te dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe pake sapi j'èli puru are nèti huri, mage mi kape hèb'a na kahèi, sèna ka bisa na'a.&gt;&gt; Aa dhu suri kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu sab'a, na, nèngu hud'i abhu gaji ku.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) it is written in God's Holy Writings that, &lt;&lt;If you use a cow to step on releasing rice/grain from its stalk, don't tie its mouth closed, so it can also eat.&gt;&gt; And it is also written, saying, &lt;&lt;Whoever works, s/he must get/receive a wage.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kape = ika mulu sapi &amp;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">kape = ika mulu sapi &amp; kerbau</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Matthew 10:10. Use the 1 Cor"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">Matthew 10:10. Use the 1 Cor 9:9 form. Check parallels. The second quotation may be a paraphrase of Numbers 18:31 or 2 Chronicles 15:7. bous: ox<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>aloaw: thresh phimow: tie shut<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>LITERALLY: for the Scripture says, "Don't muzzle the ox when it is threshing"; and, The worker deserves his wages.</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 25:4, Mateos 10:10, Lukas 10:7</note></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\HK00096C.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Sapi j'èli are-gandum<bt>Cow stepping on rice-wheat (generic-specific)</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu galaa kètu juma'at, baku sad'i sèmi mere di! Hud'i abhu ku dua do tèlu sakasii dhu lii èci, heka mi sèmi mere ho parisa ne.<bt>If there is someone who accuses a head of a congregation, don't just accept it like that (=at face value)! There must be two or three witnesses who say the same thing, only.then (should) you-sg accept (what they say) to examine him/her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kategoria: accusation, charge, formal accusation, judicial"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kategoria: accusation, charge, formal accusation, judicial accusation paradexomai: accept, acknowledge<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>ektos: outside LITERALLY: Do not accept an accusation against an elder, except upon the testimony of two or three witnesses.<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="5:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 17:6, 19:15</note><v n="20" />Ladhe miu kai ne, te ngaa na mamuri taruu madhutu d'ara sasala èèna, kai hari ne ètu madha juma'at. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, dhèu leo bani boe madhutu tatao èèna.<bt>If/when you reprimand/admonish him/her, but s/he still lives continue to live according to that wrong/sin, then reprimand/admonish them again in front of the congregation. In that way, other people will not dare/have the courage/boldness to follow that behaviour.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hamartanw: sin enwpion: before|i(20) (20) |relegxw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hamartanw: sin enwpion: before<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>elegxw: expose, reprove, correct loiroi: the others, the rest<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>phobos: fear LITERALLY: Those who continue sinning, correct them in front of all, so that the rest may have fear.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Pakako aa'i atora se'e mi juma'at dhu hag'e boe, aa baku bia cabèka. Ja'a pangèd'u sasab'a ne'e mi d'ara kacui-aai èu, ètu katanga madha Ama Lamatua dènge Yesus Kristus. Ana pajuu dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare ètu sorga, j'aj'i sakasii kahèi!<bt>Carry out all these regulations/requirements in the congregation without prejudice, and without bias/favouritism (fairly). I place this work/responsibility in your hands in front of Father God, and Yesus Kristus. The *angels in heaven that Father God has chosen are also witnesses!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="diamarturomai: charge, warn, adjure eklektos: chosen,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">diamarturomai: charge, warn, adjure eklektos: chosen, elect<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>phulassw: watch, keep [a law], observe [a law], follow, do, carry out xwpis: apart<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>prokrima: discrimination, partiality, favor, prejudgment, bias prosklisis: inclination, partiality, favoritism<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>LITERALLY: I charge you before God and Christ Jesus and the chosen angels, that you carry out these things without partiality, doing nothing with favoritism.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Baku pamèri ded'e dhèu j'aj'i kètu juma'at. Ladhe uuru ku paie-iie ne. Te ladhe miu ded'e sad'i ngara di, hèia dhèu ne tao sala, na, miu pasae sasala èèna kahèi, lula tatao na. J'aga paie ngi'u èu sèna ka mamuri mola taruu.<bt>Don't be in a hurry to elevate/install a person to be the head-leader of a congregation. Examine him carefully first. Cuz (elaboration) if you-pl install just anybody, and then that person does wrong, you-pl also bear that wrong, because of what he does. Guard yourself so that you live clean/pure continually.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sad'i ngara na dhèu = sembarang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">sad'i ngara na dhèu = sembarang orang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="xeiras: hands taxews: quickly, hastily|i(22) (22)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">xeiras: hands taxews: quickly, hastily<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>epitithemi: put upon koivwnew: share, participate in<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>hamartias: sin allotrios: to another<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>hagnos: pure terew: weakness<span class="Italic">(22) (22) </span>LITERALLY: Do not lay hands on someone hastily, lest you share another persons sins; keep yourself pure.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ja'a tadèngi èu kabake pèd'a taruu. Be'a risi nèti deo ne'e, èu pab'ali èi dènge anggor ciki tao sèmi èi na'i. Baku minu dhoka èi iia di.<bt>I've heard that you often have stomach/abdomen sickness/pain. It would be good if from now you mix water with a little wine (loan), as medicine/remedy. Don't drink just plain water.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hudropitew: drink water oinos: wine|i(23) (23)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hudropitew: drink water oinos: wine<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>oligos: a little khraomai: use<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>stomakhos: stomach puknas: frequent<span class="Italic">(23) (23) </span>astheneias: weakness, sickness, infirmity, ailment, illness LITERALLY: No longer drink water, but use a little wine for your stomach and your frequent illnesses.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ladhe paie-iie! Abhu sasala dhèu dhu cèu mema. Rèngu d'ai mèka madha hakim, te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a le èèna. Te ngaa abhu dhèu leo kahèi dhu nèbhu-nèbhu ku, heka sasala ra cèu kèna.<bt>Take a good look! There are people whose wrongs/sins are immediately obvious/visible. Before they arrive in front of the judge (loan), everyone already knows it. But there are other people also, who have a long time go by before their wrong/sin becomes visible/obvious.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="prodelos: clear, conspicuous, obvious proagw: lead,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">prodelos: clear, conspicuous, obvious proagw: lead, precede, go before<span class="Italic">(24) (24) </span>epakolouthw: follow after, come later LITERALLY: The sins of some men are obvious, going before them into judgment, but certain ones follow after;<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge dhèu dhu tao be'a sèra. Abhu mema dhu led'a. Te ngaa cahag'e pahuni-pahuni tao dhu be'a. Te ngaa masi ka sèmi èèna, ngaa dhu rèngu tao sèra, nèbhu-nèbhu cèu asa li'u kahèi. Bisa boe pahuni tatao dhu be'a.<bt>It's the same way with people who do good. There are those who are immediately obvious/visible. But there are others who do good things in secret. But even that being the case, what they have done, will eventually become obvious/visible. Good things cannot be hidden.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="led'a = kantara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">led'a = kantara</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hwsautws: similarly prodelos: obvious|i(25) (25) |rkruptw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hwsautws: similarly prodelos: obvious<span class="Italic">(25) (25) </span>kruptw: hide LITERALLY: Similarly, the good deeds are obvious, and others cannot be hidden.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ènu dènge lamatua na<bt>Slaves and masters</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Abhu lamatua dhu ènu na parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Rèngu hud'i pakab'ua lamatua ra, sèna ka dhèu leo abhu boe j'ara ho padhai lii pamanahu kolongara Ama Lamatua, aa pamud'e dènge lii aj'a-nori èdhi.<bt>There are masters whose slaves believe in the Lord Yesus. They must give respect.honour to their masters, so that outsiders have no reasons to speak bringing down Father God's name/reputation, and scorn/belittle/disparage our-inc teaching.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamud'e = pandang enteng, remehkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">pamud'e = pandang enteng, remehkan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hosoi: as many as zugos: yoke|i(1)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hosoi: as many as zugos: yoke<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>despote: master, lord, owner time: honor<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>aksios: worthy, deserving hegeomai: consider, think, regard, count<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>blasphemew: slander, speak evil of, defame, blaspheme LITERALLY: As many as are under the yoke of slavery, let them consider their masters worthy of all honor, that the name of God and the teaching not be spoken evil of.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2a" />Abhu ènu dhu lamatua na parcaya le Lamatua Yesus. Ènu ne bisa boe pahaha lamatua na, lula lamatua na dhu parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Masi ka tasamia èèna ka, rèngu hud'i lalau ku pabe'a risi hari lamatua ra, lula rèngu dènge rèngu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, dhèu parcaya dhu hud'i mamuri pasue ku.<bt>There are slaves whose masters believe in the Lord Yesus. Slaves are not allowed to scorn/belittle/disparage his/her master because that master believes in the Lord Yesus. Even more they must serve their master even better, because they (slaves) and they (masters), are together/fellow believers who must live in reciprocal love.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kataphronew: think down on, scorn, despise,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kataphronew: think down on, scorn, despise, treat with contempt douleuw: serve, perform the duties of a slave, obey<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>euergesia: service, kindness antilambanw: benefit, take part in, devote oneself to, practice<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: And he who has a believing master should not look down on him, because they are brothers, but rather serve him, because those who benefit from their service are believers and beloved. Teach these things and exhort [them to do them].</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii aj'a-nori dhu sala, dènge a'oto dhu be'a<bt>False/incorrect teaching, and good reward/profit</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2b" />Timotius! Aj'a aa'i-aa'i se, aa pa'èra d'ara dhèu sarani sèra, sèna ka tao madhutu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Timotius! Teach all this, and encourage/inspire the Christians to follow/obey all of it.</bt><v n="3" />Lii aj'a-nori èdhi dhu lèke èèna, j'aj'i kapua nèti d'ara mamuri èdhi dhu pakarej'e d'ara Lamatua. Te ngaa dhèu dhu nori leo nèti lii aj'a se'e, dhèu sèra dhu core eele le lii Lamatua Yesus Kristus dhu lèke.<bt>Our-inc true/correct teaching is the basis/foundation of our way of life that pleases God's insides. But people who teach something different from these teachings, those people have rejected the Lord Yesus Kristus' true/correct teaching.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèni = dasar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">kèni = dasar</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heterodidaskalew: teach a different thing, teach"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">heterodidaskalew: teach a different thing, teach other doctrine eusebeia: godliness, godly faith, religion, piety<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>proserxomai: follow, agree with, accords with prosexw: pay attention to:<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>hugiainw: be healthy, sound LITERALLY: If anyone teaches different doctrine and does not agree with the sound words which are of our Lord Jesus Christ, and godly teaching,<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dhèu sèmi èèna, padedha iisi, te ngaa goa. Papèd'a rèngu ka d'èi dhoka tenge lii langu, aa pab'ala d'ara lii. J'ara se'e se ka dhu tao dhèu ho: tèka d'ara, patao-palaha, pa'ele iie kolongara dhèu leo, aa pangee dhu lèke boe mi dhèu leo.<bt>People of that sort, are arrogant (lit. elevate themselves), but dumb! Their disease is liking to make disputes (out of nothing, Idiom) and arguing/debating over words. All this makes people: jealous/hateful, fighting with each other (doublet), damaging other people's good name/reputation, and just suspicious of other people in incorrect ways.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabhènga = goa, stupid"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">tabhènga = goa, stupid</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tuphow: puffed up, inflated, conceited, arrogant,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">tuphow: puffed up, inflated, conceited, arrogant, proud epistamai: understand<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>nosew: have a morbid craving, be ailing with, sick zetesis: investigation, controversy, discussion, debate, argument<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>logomaxia: dispute about words, word battle phthonos: envy, jealousy<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>eris: strife, discord, contention, quarreling blasphemia: slander, defamation, blasphemy, harsh and abusive language<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>huponoia: suspicion, insinuations, conjecture, secret opinion poneros: wicked, evil, unjust, malicious, false<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>LITERALLY: he is conceited, understanding nothing, but having a morbid craving for controversy and disputes about words, out of which come envy, strife, slander, evil suspicions,</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dhèu sèmi se'e, loe boe patao-palaha. Ngangee ra karehe bia. Re'a heka mia ka dhu be'a.<bt>People of that sort keep upsetting things /causing disruptions/disorder endlessly. Their thinking is heavily rotten. They don't know any more what is true/correct.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="diaparatribe: mutual or constant irritation, wrangling,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">diaparatribe: mutual or constant irritation, wrangling, dispute diephtheirw: spoil, morally ruined, depraved<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>nous: mind, attitude, way of thinking, mental and moral state of being aposterew: steal, rob, deprive<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>nomizw: think, imagine, consider, believe porismos: means of gain, means of profit<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>eusebeia: godliness, piety, LITERALLY: constant wrangling between men of depraved mind and deprived of the truth, imagining godliness to be a means of [financial] profit.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rèngu ngee, ladhe rèngu maj'èni dènge j'ara-j'ara agama, rèngu bisa j'aj'i dhèu kaja-su'i.<bt>They think that if they are diligent with the ways of religion, they can become wealthy (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Mema, agama bisa hia a'oto mi dhèu. Te mamuri dènge Lamatua èèna ka dhu hia dhèu karej'e nèti ngaa dhu rèngu unu. Èèna, heka agama dhu lèke kèna.<bt>It is true that religion can bring benefit to people. Cuz (elaboration) life with God is what makes people happy with what they own. Only then is it true religion.</bt><v n="7" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Lod'o rara iisi èdhi, èdhi tèti boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa asa rai-haha ne. Aa ladhe lod'o madhe, tèti boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa kahèi nèti rai-haha ne.<bt>Remember well! When we-inc were born, we did not bring anything into this world. And when we die, we will not take anything from this world.</bt><v n="8" />De sad'i dènge nganga'a, mèdha-papake sèra sa nia le!<bt>So, as long as there is food and clothes, that is enough!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dai ~ nia = cukup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">dai ~ nia = cukup</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu neo kaja, mud'a titu kèna lèke dadugu-rariu rupa-rupa, aa lèke sasii g'ana-kariu, lula rèngu pangee dhoka mèdha-panyau di. J'ara se'e se ka dhu pa'ele iie mamuri rèngu.<bt>But (as for) people who want/yearn to be rich, it's very easy for them to be affected by various sorts of temptations/seductions, and be ensnared left-right, because they are only just thinking about belongings/possessions. All that thoroughly destroys their life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasii = jerat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">sasii = jerat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boulomai: desire, wish, want ploutew: be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">boulomai: desire, wish, want ploutew: be rich<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>empiptw: fall into, involved in peirasmos: test, temptation, enticement to sin<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>pagis: trap, snare, entanglement epithmia: desire, lust, longing [in a bad sense]<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>anonetos: useless, thoughtless, devoid of sound reason, unintelligent, foolish, unwise, irrational blaberos: harmful, hurtful<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>buthizw: sink, plunge, drag down olethros: destruction, ruin, death, corruption<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>apwleia: destruction, utter destruction, annihilation LITERALLY: But those who desire to be rich fall into temptation and a snare and many useless and harmful desires, which plunge men into ruin and destruction;<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Te sue doi-dhari, èèna j'aj'i mi amo nèti rupa-rupa bhabhelu. Abhu dhèu cahag'e magèle dhoka doi-dhari di, toke ra pakaj'èu nèti parcaya ra dhu lèke. Hèia rèngu mesa ra pa'ele iie mamuri ra.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) loving money, is the root from all sorts of evil. There are some people who pursue/hunt money, to.point.that they have already strayed/diverged/deviated far from their true/correct belief. So (consequently) they themselves have destroyed their own lives.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="magèle = kejar, buru"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">magèle = kejar, buru</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hriza: root, beginning from which something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">hriza: root, beginning from which something grows, source. Blass-Debrunner 273, definite predicate nouns preceding the verb are anarthrous (=theos een ho logos). So "the root" rather than "a root". kakos: evil, bad, moral evil<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>philarguria: love of money, avarice, miserliness oregw: aspire to, crave, strive for, desire, covet<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>apoplanaw: mislead, wander away, go astray, depart peripeirw: pierce through<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>odynee: pain, pang, sorrows LITERALLY: For the love of money is the root of all evils, from which certain ones having desired, have departed from the faith and pierced themselves with many pains.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kèpe pa'èra-èra parcaya èu<bt>Hold firmly to your belief</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Timotius! Èu ne, dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. De pakaj'èu iisi nèti bhabhelu-katub'a aa'i-aa'i. Mamuri mola-mèci. Mamuri madhutu dad'èi Lamatua ètu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i ra. Parcaya taruu mi Yesus Kristus. Sue dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra. Pa'èra ètu d'ara j'aj'èra. Mamuri d'ara be'a dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Timotius! You are Father God's possession. So, retreat/shy away very far from everything that is evil (doublet). Live clean/pure/holy. Live according to God's will in every matter. Continue to believe/trust in Yesus Kristus. Love all people. Endure/persevere in difficulty (=don't give up). Live well/good/nicely with everyone.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Compare Gal 5:23 pheugw: flee, shun,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">Compare Gal 5:23 pheugw: flee, shun, avoid, escape from, keep away from<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>diwkw: persue, aim at, strive for, seek after, aspire to dikaiosune: righteousness, uprightness [in the moral and religious sense]<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>eusebeia: godliness, piety, devout and entirely correct religious attitude pistis: faith<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>agape: love hupomone: endurance, patience, longsuffering, steadfastness, fortitude, perseverance<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>praupathia: gentleness, meekness, inner spirit resulting in meekness, gentleness of feeling LITERALLY: But you, o man of God, flee these things, and persue righteousness, godliness, faith, love, endurance, gentleness.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Sab'a pa'èra-èra dènge d'ara kateme, sèna ka pakako lii holo-nori aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi parcaya. Lamatua paroa le èu, ho abhu mamuri taa-taa. De liku pa'èra-èra mamuri èèna, baku patalale eele. Aa èu dhu peka le ètu madha dhèu ae, lula-nèti parcaya èu mi Lamatua Yesus.<bt>Make every effort to carry out/set in motion all the teachings that we-inc believe. God has called you to get eternal life (=that does not end). So, strongly embrace that life, and don't let it go. And you-sg have made known/told before many people your faith in the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="agwnizomai: struggle, carry on a contest,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">agwnizomai: struggle, carry on a contest, strive, fight agwn: struggle, contest, athletic event<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>epilambanomai: grasp, take hold of, obtain tees aiooniou zooees: CHECK.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>kalew: call homologew: confess, declare, also V. 13 but in a different context (Jesus vs. people doing it); 1Cor 12:3, Rom 10:9, Phil 2:11<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>LITERALLY: Struggle in the good contest of faith to obtain eternal life, into which you were called and confessed the good confession before many witnesses.</Message></Annotation><v n="13-14" />De nèti deo ne'e, ja'a manèngi èu pa'èki lii pajaji sèmi ne'e: tao madhutu lii paredha aa'i-aa'i nèti Lamatua Yesus. Baku sisu èci sa hèi, sèna ka dhèu baku rèdhi sasala èu. Tao madhutu aa'i-aa'i ra dènge mola-mola toke lod'o mamai hari Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus. Ja'a manèngi èu jaji sèmi èèna ètu madha Ama Lamatua. Nèngu ka dhu hia le samanga mi dhu mamuri aa'i-aa'i ra. Ja'a manèngi kahèi èu jaji sèmi èèna ètu madha Yesus Kristus. Nèngu dhu peka paled'a le, lula-nèti ngi'u Nèngu, ètu madha gubernur Pontius Pilatus.<bt>So now, I ask that you bind a promise like this: Follow/obey all of the Lord Yesus' commands. Don't violate/contravene/transgress even one, so people can't find anything wrong with you. Do it all correctly/truly until the day when our-inc Head, Yesus Kristus, comes back again. I ask that you promise that before Father God. He is the one who has given life.force to everything that lives. I also ask that you promise that before Yesus Kristus. He is the one who openly told about Himself before gubernur Pontius Pilatus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sisu = 1) melawan, bantah, 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">sisu = 1) melawan, bantah, 2) langgar, trespass, transgress</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paraggellw: encourage, charge, command, exhort, ggive"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">paraggellw: encourage, charge, command, exhort, ggive orders, instruct zwogonew: give life<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>martureesantos teen kaleen homologian: testify, bear witness. To the truth, according to John; not to the Church's confession that Jesus Christ is Lord, as in 12. LITERALLY: I charge you before God, who gives life to everything, and Jesus Christ, who testified the good confession before Pontius Pilate,<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>UBS commentary: scope of 11-12 may be Timothy's ordination, his baptism, or the whole letter. tepew: keep, obey, fulfill<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>aspilos: without blemish, unstained, spotless anepilemptos: irreproachable, free from reproach, reproof<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>mexri: until epiphaneia: appearance<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>LITERALLY: keep the commandment spotless, free from reproach until the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ,</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:13-14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 18:37</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />Lamatua Yesus dhu kapai risi, Nèngu ka dhu nèd'u koasa!<bt>The Lord Yesus who is great(er), He is the one who holds power/authority!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu èèna, Dhèu Aae Kapai nèti dhèu aae aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>He is the Big King from among all kings.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Nèngu èèna, Lamatua Kapai nèti lamatua aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>And He is the Big Lord from among all lords.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ropa d'ai lod'o na,<bt>And just at the right time,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lamatua paled'a aa'i-aa'i si.<bt>God1 will make everything become visible/known/obvious.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kairos: time, definite and fixed time"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">kairos: time, definite and fixed time idios: ones own, appropriate, proper<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>deiknumi: show, point out, be manifest, reveal, make known makarios: for tunate, blessed, source of highest joy, state of true well being. 1:11.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>monos: only dunastes: ruler<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>LITERALLY: which in his times he will show, the blessed and only ruler, the King of kings and Lord of lords,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />Dhoka Nèngu mesa Na di, dhu madhe boe.<bt>Only He himself is the one who doesn't die.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa dhu dhèu rai-haha taha boe laladhe.<bt>He lives in light which humans cannot stand/endure seeing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Abhu boe dhèu èci sa ladhe rèdhi Ne.<bt>There is not one person who can see Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lii-lii pakab'ua dhodhoka mi Nèngu di!<bt>All words of respect/honour is only to Him!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Koasa aa'i-aa'i, ètu kacui-aai Na, toke d'ai mia-mia!<bt>All power/authority is in His hands until forever!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">D'ai sange ne'e ka! Tare'a!<bt>That's how it is! Amin!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="athanasia: immortality phws: light. Knowledge? Lack"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">athanasia: immortality phws: light. Knowledge? Lack of sin? Purity? Not a successful metaphor for Pidgin speakers, but all over the Bible.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>oikoew: dwell, inhabit aprositos: unapproachable, not able to be approached<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>time: honor, respect, esteem, reverence, worship, adoration kratos: power, rule, sovereignty<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>LITERALLY: who only has immortality, dwelling in unapproachable light, whom no man has seen, neither can see; to whom is honor and power forever; amen.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pasanèd'e hia dhèu kaja<bt>Warning for rich people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Peka mi dhèu kaja ètu rai-haha ne, ho rèngu baku padedha iisi, aa baku dhoka maena mèdha-panyau rèngu di. Te mèdha-panyau sèra, bèli-camèd'a èla aa'i. De dhu lèke ka, maena dhoka mi Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri di. Te Nèngu ka dhu pala-bagi èdhi ngaa-ngaa dhu èdhi parluu, sèna ka èdhi mamuri dènge karej'e.<bt>Tell the rich people in this world to not be proud/arrogant, and to not be dependent only on their wealth/belongings. Cuz (elaboration) all that wealth/belongings will later disappear/end/be finished. It is better for them to hope/be dependent on the God who lives. Cuz He is the one who divided out to us-inc everything that we-inc need, so that we-inc can live in happiness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="plousios: rich, rich person aiwn: age|i(17)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">plousios: rich, rich person aiwn: age<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hupselophronew: be proud, [think high] high minded, haughty, proud, insolence elpizw: hope, set ones hope on<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>ploutos: wealth, riches adelotes: uncertainty, uncertain<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>parexw: grant plousiws: richly<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>apolausis: enjoyment LITERALLY: Charge those who are rich in this age not to be proud, nor to set their hope on uncertain riches, but [to set their hope] upon God who grants us all things richly to enjoy,<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Peka dènge ra, ho pake kakaja sèra sèna ka tao dhu be'a. Rèngu hud'i maj'èni tao dhu be'a. Rèngu hud'i bhoke kacui-aai ho soru-bara dhèu leo, aa d'èi pala-bagi mèngi-nale dhu rèngu abhu nèti Lamatua.<bt>Tell them to use their wealth/belongings to do what is good. They must be diligent to do good. They must open their hands (=be willingly generous) to help other people, and like to/regularly divide out the blessings which they got from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="agathoergew: do good, practice doing things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">agathoergew: do good, practice doing things for others kalos: good<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>eumetadotos: generous, ready to share worldly goods koinwnikos: liberal, generous, fellowship of sympathy<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>LITERALLY: to do good, to be rich in good deeds, to be generous, willing to share,</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Hèia ra pakaboko mèdha-panyau ho j'aj'i mi kapua dhu èra, hia mamuri ra bèli-camèd'a. Ka rèngu unu mamuri dhu dènge kab'ua.<bt>So then they gather together wealth/belongings as a strong/firm foundation/basis for their life in the future. And they have a life that has value.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhii-manèro = umur panjang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">madhii-manèro = umur panjang</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="apothesaurizw: store up, store away, lay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">apothesaurizw: store up, store away, lay up. Sermon on the Mount, Matthew 6:19-20. themelios: foundation, basis for receiving good things<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>mellw: be destined epilambanomai: grasp, take hold of<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>zwe: life ontoos: real, true<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>LITERALLY: storing up for themselves a good foundation for the time to come, that they may take hold of the true life.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus pa'èle sasuri na<bt>Paulus finishes his letter</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Timotius! J'aga paie aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua pangèd'u le mi èu. Baku lamu padhai lii dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua. Baku padhai lii kaj'alu dhu pakab'ua boe Ama Lamatua. Sanèd'e, ee! Te abhu dhèu dhu pangee, na, rèngu dhèu d'èlu-mèu. Te ngaa &lt;mamèu&gt; rèngu sèra dhu hèb'a hua. Baku lamu pab'ala lii padhai dènge ra.<bt>Timotius! Guard carefully everything that Father God has placed in your-sg hands. Don't go along with involving yourself in nonsense/pointless chatter. Don't do pointless talk which doesn't bring respect/honour to God. Remember, é! There are people who consider themselves to be smart/clever. But their 'smartness' has no basis/foundation whatsoever. Don't go debate with them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText=", 4:1, 5:8; phulassw: watch, guard,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">, 4:1, 5:8; phulassw: watch, guard, keep safe, protect paratheekee: entrusted, committed to 2 Tim 1:12, 14<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>ektrepw: turn away from, avoid bebelos: profane, godless, useless, profitless<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>kenophwnia: chatter, babble, empty talk antithesis: opposition, contradiction, objection<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>pseudwnumos: falsely called, falsely named gnwsis: knowledge<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>LITERALLY: O Timothy, guard that which has been entrusted to you, avoid godless chatter and contradictions, which are falsely called knowledge,</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adhe aai = telapak tangan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">adhe aai = telapak tangan ; hèb'a hua = mulu kosong ~ sonde ada pung guna ; mi = (plural) ~ ma = (singular) CHECK@@</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Abhu dhèu cahag'e lèka lii aj'a-nori dhu kapod'e-kabèli sèra, toke ra sero eele nèti parcaya ra dhu lèke mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>There are some people who believe in those deceptive teachings, to the point that they deviate from their true/correct faith/belief in Father God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sero eele = serong (loan)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z">sero eele = serong (loan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama Lamatua pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi dedha èu dènge angalai mu si aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>I ask that Father God show/demonstrate His goodness/kindness/grace to you-sg and all your companions.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epaggelomenoi: giving themselves out as experts,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:54:52Z" status="Information">epaggelomenoi: giving themselves out as experts, laying claim to expertise in knowledge astoxew: miss the mark 5:8 1:19 4:1<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>LITERALLY: which some having professed concerning the faith, have missed the mark. Grace be with you.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Saloom,<bt>Syalom,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Paulus<bt>Paulus</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>